  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This 2023 preprint by Danni Yu, Luyang Li, Hang Su, and Matteo Fuoli investigates whether large language models can meaningfully assist corpus annotation for pragmatic and discourse analysis, using the speech act of apology as a test case. Posted on arXiv and subsequently versioned into a peer-reviewed journal publication, the work has attracted three citing works spanning computational linguistics, social sciences, and corpus-based media analysis, signaling early cross-disciplinary uptake in a rapidly moving methodological conversation.</p>\n\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The study sits at a productive intersection of corpus linguistics and natural language processing, asking a practical but consequential question: can LLM-assisted annotation reduce the burden of manual labeling without sacrificing the interpretive precision that fine-grained pragmatic analysis demands? By grounding the inquiry in apology\u2014a well-theorized speech act with established annotation schemes\u2014the authors provide a concrete benchmark against which LLM performance can be evaluated. This methodological anchoring makes the contribution legible both to linguists skeptical of automation and to NLP researchers seeking humanistic evaluation criteria. The existence of a versioned journal counterpart (in the International Journal of Corpus Linguistics) further signals that the core findings were deemed sufficiently robust for formal peer review.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The citing landscape, though still modest at three works, is notably heterogeneous and intellectually substantive. One citing preprint\u2014\"ChatGPT for Text Annotation? Mind the Hype!\"\u2014directly engages the same evaluative question from a social-science perspective, suggesting the work feeds into a broader, somewhat skeptical methodological debate about the reliability of LLM-generated labels. A second citation appears in an EMNLP proceedings paper on open-science infrastructure for computational linguistics, positioning Yu et al.'s work as part of the evidence base for reproducible corpus practices. A third citation, in Humanities and Social Sciences Communications, applies related approaches to media discourse analysis, illustrating how the methodological framework travels into applied corpus studies. Citing institutions include Hong Kong Polytechnic University, the National University of Singapore, and Pennsylvania State University, reflecting the study's reach across Asia-Pacific and North American research communities.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The alignment with the UN Sustainable Development Goal of Quality Education\u2014scored with considerable confidence\u2014is a meaningful contextual signal. Corpus-based pragmatics and annotation methodology are core components of applied linguistics curricula, and research that lowers the cost and technical threshold of corpus annotation has direct implications for how educators and students engage with large language datasets. This connection positions the work not only as a research contribution but as a potential resource for pedagogical innovation in language education and computational humanities programs.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, the paper represents an early but credible contribution to what is becoming a crowded and contested space: the use of generative AI as a labor-saving device in qualitative linguistic annotation. Its strength lies in empirical specificity\u2014anchoring broad claims about LLM capability in a single, well-understood pragmatic phenomenon\u2014while its cross-disciplinary uptake suggests the questions it raises resonate well beyond corpus pragmatics. As the field continues to debate the appropriate role of automation in interpretive linguistic work, this study is positioned to serve as a useful methodological reference point.</p>",
